{"parse":{"title":"The Abandoned Soldier","pageid":33994260,"revid":846810608,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox vevent\" style=\"width:22em;width: 22em; line-height: 1.4em; text-align: left; float:right;\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" class=\"summary\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;font-size: 125%; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic\">The Abandoned Soldier (TAS)</th></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Artist</th><td class=\"attendee\">\n<a href=\"/w/index.php?title=James_Napier_(sculptor)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"James Napier (sculptor) (page does not exist)\">James Napier</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Year</th><td>\n2007</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Type</th><td class=\"category\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/Resin\" title=\"Resin\">Resin</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Location</th><td>\n<a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Cardiff_Castle_(placeholder)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Cardiff Castle (placeholder) (page does not exist)\">Unknown</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Unknown_(placeholder)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Unknown (placeholder)\">Unknown</a></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><i><b>The Abandoned Soldier</b></i> is a sculpture created in 2007 by sculptor James Napier that was modelled after British ex-soldier Lance Corporal Daniel Twiddy.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Interpretation\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Interpretation</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Conservation\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Conservation</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Abandoned_Soldier&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The sculpture <i>The Abandoned Soldier</i> (TAS) was made for the <a href=\"/wiki/BBC\" title=\"BBC\">BBC</a> documentary <i>Power to the People</i> <sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> to be erected in Trafalgar Square, and made an appearance on Newsnight as well as the front page of the Independent newspaper. TAS was initially housed at <a href=\"/wiki/Combat_Stress\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Combat Stress\">Combat Stress</a>, a charitable organisation for ex-servicemen and women, before being moved with the help of the Royal Electrical and Mechanical Engineers to the <a href=\"/wiki/National_Memorial_Arboretum\" title=\"National Memorial Arboretum\">National Memorial Arboretum</a> in Staffordshire to launch The Abandoned Soldier Project. The sculpture has subsequently been moved to Cardiff Castle, then to Exeter Castle for the War Art Exhibition in June 2011, and was filmed as part of a Channel 5 documentary.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> From there it was moved to the Rhondda Heritage Park at <a href=\"/wiki/Trehafod\" title=\"Trehafod\">Trehafod</a>. \n</p><p>In April 2012, the sculpture was moved back to Cardiff Castle as a permanent 'base'. In the Summer of 2013, the head piece was removed from the base and taken on a tour of Wales.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> The high points included; The summit of Mount Snowdon and Portmeirion.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> In May 2014 the sculpture was part of an installation by Themis Jones, installed at the Hay Festival of Literature and Art. In July 2014 he returned to his main 'base' at Cardiff Castle and will stand as a lasting reminder of the trauma of War, until 2018.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Interpretation\">Interpretation</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Abandoned_Soldier&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Interpretation\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The statue was created in remembrance of soldiers who have suffered the after effects of armed conflict and are not being treated like the heroes they truly are.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> The sculpture was modelled after Lance Corporal Daniel Twiddy, who had been wounded in 2003 by friendly fire and shrapnel while in <a href=\"/wiki/Basra\" title=\"Basra\">Basra</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> Twiddy had received several wounds from shrapnel, which included wounds to the face from a 'Blue on Blue' incident.<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Conservation\">Conservation</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Abandoned_Soldier&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Conservation\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In 2010 concerns were made over the stability of the sculpture and that the resin material might disintegrate.<sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> Concerns were also raised about the sculpture's lack of a permanent display location. There have been attempts at petitioning for a more permanent location as well as fundraising efforts for a bronze version of the statue.\n</p><p>The sculpture now has a piece of music, commissioned by the TAS Project, written and sung by Bethan Myfanwy Hughes, a civilian trauma nurse and also a member of the Territorial Army.<sup id=\"cite_ref-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Abandoned_Soldier&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"https://thepsychologist.bps.org.uk/volume-25/edition-1/big-picture-abandoned-soldier\">[1]</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/power_to_the_people/6613759.stm\">Power To The People: The Battle of Trafalgar Square</a> BBC News</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.welshicons.org.uk/news/cardiff/cardiff-castle-welcomes-the-abandoned-soldier/\">Cardiff Castle Welcomes The Abandoned Soldier</a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://archive.is/20121224155540/http://www.welshicons.org.uk/news/cardiff/cardiff-castle-welcomes-the-abandoned-soldier/\">Archived</a> 2012-12-24 at <a href=\"/wiki/Archive.is\" title=\"Archive.is\">Archive.is</a> WelshIcons.org.uk</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://cardiffian.jomec.co.uk/article/forgotten-soldier-statue-erected-cardiff-castle\">Forgotten soldier statue erected by Cardiff Castle</a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20120131225935/http://cardiffian.jomec.co.uk/article/forgotten-soldier-statue-erected-cardiff-castle\">Archived</a> 2012-01-31 at the <a href=\"/wiki/Wayback_Machine\" title=\"Wayback Machine\">Wayback Machine</a>. The Cardiffian</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/100933196@N03/sets/72157649153200768/\">[2]</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=69WD1zeCcXU\">[3]</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-15533875\">Garden of remembrance at heritage park to fallen troops</a> BBC News</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-8\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.cavgds.co.uk/assets/89/March_09_Newsletter.pdf\">The Abandoned Soldier</a> The Cavalry and Guards Club, 127 Newsletter, March 2009</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-9\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-9\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2011/02/12/sculpture-tribute-to-soldiers-hardship-91466-28158852/\">Sculpture tribute to soldiers\u2019 hardship</a> Wales Online</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-10\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-10\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/5034672.stm\">[4]</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-11\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-11\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.rctbusinessclub.co.uk/7820.html\">Rhondda Heritage Park\u2019s Garden of Remembrance 2011</a> Rhondda Heritage Business Club</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-12\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-12\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"n